                                                                                                               SPORT BRIEFS
                                                    Srinath to officiate in second semi-final
    Calcutta: The ICC Thursday named former India pacer Javagal Srinath as the Match Referee for the second semi-final of the Champions Trophy between New Zealand and Pakistan scheduled for Saturday. Australia rsquo;s Simon Taufel and Ian Gould of England will be the on-field umpires, while Australian Daryl Harper and Steve Davis will be the third and fourth officials for the match.
    Replacement
    Calcutta: The International Cricket Council event technical committee Thursday approved that David Hussey could replace Michael Clarke, who has been suffering from lower back problem.
    Bracken injury
    Calcutta: Nursing a knee-injury, Australian left-arm pacer Nathan Bracken will have to sit out of the Champions League Twenty20 tournament in India next week to undergo a surgery. The 32-year-old Bracken was scheduled to play for New South Wales.
    Puttick in
    Calcutta: The Champions League technical committee, Thursday, approved left-handed opening batsman Andrew Puttick as Graeme Smith rsquo;s replacement in the 15-man Cape Cobras squad for the October 8-23 tournament. Smith was withdrawn to continue his rehabilitation from elbow surgery.
    De Villiers out
    Johannesburg: The Delhi DareDevils will miss the services of AB de Villiers in their Champions League T20 campaign as CSA has withdrawn him from the tournament due to a lower back pain.
    Afridi view
    Calcutta: Shahid Afridi has praised captain Younis Khan for the team rsquo;s improved performance. ldquo;In the last three to four months, the guys have done a great job and the credit goes to the captain because he kept the team united, rdquo; Afridi has said.
    Rugby    Mumbai: The disciplinary committee of the 76th All India and South Asia Rugby Division-I tournament Thursday declared Maharashtra State Police guilty of violent conduct and banned the side for one year from playing any national tournament. Meanwhile, Uzbekistan will fight it out with holders Army Red Friday in the final of the meet at the Bombay Gymkhana here.
    CWG concern
    Sydney: Australia rsquo;s Commonwealth Games chief said Thursday he cannot guarantee the safety of his country rsquo;s athletes at next year rsquo;s games in New Delhi, and will let them decide whether they want to compete.   Bopanna falls
  Kuala Lumpur: Rohan Bopanna lost to world No. 12 Fernando Gonzalez of Chile 4-6, 6-3, 4-6 in the second round of the Kuala Lumpur Open here Thursday.
  
